Come with me on a day trip to Martha’s Vineyard! 

We took the ferry out of New Bedford on Friday for a quick 45 minute ride to Martha’s Vineyard. Believe it or not, this was my first time visiting! Some highlights for me included the cliffs and lighthouse at Aquinnah, the charming architecture and views around the island, and lunch at @19rawoysterbar. We had perfect spring weather for exploring and I made sure to bring my biggest @barringtongifts bag, my St. Charles Yacht Tote, to hold my purse, camera, and extra sweater, and it even left room for treasures to bring back from the island. I’ve mentioned this before, but the St. Charles is the ideal bag for travel— it holds SO much. The endless personalization options don’t hurt either 😉 Mine is the new Periwinkle Floral Fans pattern with a giant monogram in Periwinkle/Grass and it is perfection. #barringtongifts #marthasvineyard #marthasvineyardstyle

My love for coastal New England runs deep. So when I found @haverhillcollection years ago, fine 14k gold, customizable birthstone jewelry made in coastal Rhode Island, I immediately fell in love. I’ve been wearing my personalized birthstone necklace with my kids’ birthstones for years (and rarely take it off— it’s wearable in the shower, during exercise, sleep, etc.,) and I have gifted Haverhill pieces for milestone birthdays and special occasions. A personalized birthstone piece is the perfect Mother’s Day gift for any mom! 

I knew I wanted to memorialize my most recent trip to @oceanhouseri, Newport, and Martha’s Vineyard, and the Rosecliff Circle Diamond necklace was the perfect piece to remind me of this special trip. I wore it the entire time and it will always remind me of this special place that I hold dear to my heart. 

I’m honored that @haverhillcollection gave me a code for you to use, just in time for Mother’s Day (their turnaround time is FAST!) You can use code HANNAH15 for 15% off. #haverhillcollection #finejewelry #mothersdaygift #madeinnewengland

How are we back here? How can history possibly repeat itself in such a barbaric way? Never again, we said. Never forget. But here we are.

As I’ve been processing what’s happening in Israel, I’ve had a lot of thoughts about my own Jewish identity. In times like these, I often feel like I’m not “Jewish enough” to own the pain that my people are experiencing. I’m not particularly religious. My family is not Israeli. I went to Jewish day school and my kids went to Jewish preschool, but I rarely go to temple. I don’t fast on Yom Kippur. If I remember correctly, I sprinkled my Bat Mitzvah speech with some choice phrases about being agnostic. But for me, it has always been about culture. Family traditions. My ancestors. 

As someone with somewhat of an online presence (albeit very small,) I’ve shied away from getting “too political.” I never want to ruffle any feathers or turn people away from my little space. But I can no longer stay silent. Whether you are Jewish or not, whether you have a connection to Israel or not, this is about humanity. Read the news. Watch the horrific clips. Educate yourselves. Don’t hide behind not knowing enough. 

I’ve built my life and career around bringing beauty into the world through design, art, and creating. It sometimes feels silly. Sharing interior design, outfits, tablescapes, products. When people are dying. When unimaginable history is repeating itself. I’m not going to stop sharing the beauty. But I just couldn’t continue on without first addressing this nightmare.

The blue and white plate in this photo was brought to America from Eastern Europe by my Jewish great great grandmother. I may not be Israeli or observant or religious at all, really, but I am Jewish. My family is Jewish. And I stand for humanity.
